Definition :
 Bacterial fever is an infection caused by bacteria that leads to a high body temperature (fever) and other symptoms.
Symptoms :
-High body temperature (fever)
-Chills
-Sweat
-Headache
-Muscle aches
-Cough or sore throat
-Urinary tract infection (UTI) symptoms (e.g., burning during urination)
-Skin infections (e.g., redness, swelling, warmth)
Treatment :
-Antibiotics (prescribed by a doctor)
-Rest and hydration (plenty of fluids)
-Over-the-counter medications (e.g., Panadol ) for fever reduction
-Pain relief medications (e.g., acetaminophen, ibuprofen)
-Warm compresses for skin infections
-Urinary tract infection (UTI) treatment (e.g., antibiotics)
Note: 
Always consult a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment. Antibiotics only work against bacterial infections, not viral infections!

October 28, 2024
In experiments designed to learn more about the threat from the H5N1 avian flu virus spreading from cows to people, researchers found that an isolate from a sick dairy worker may be capable of replicating in human airway cells, is pathogenic in mice and ferrets, and can transmit among ferrets by respiratory droplets.

The team, based at the University of Wisconsin at Madison and Japan, reported its findings today in Nature. Working in a high-containment lab, the researchers used an H5N1 isolate grown from the eye of a dairy worker who had experienced conjunctivitis after exposure to infected cows.

They found that the virus has a PB2-E627K mutation that has been seen in H5N1 viruses that replicate in mammals.

In their multipart investigation, they found that the virus was sensitive to most antivirals, including favipiravir, baloxavir marboxil, and zanamivir, but was less sensitive to oseltamivir, according to a press release from the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID), which funded much of the work.

Tests using human cornea and lung cells found that the virus was able to replicate. And, in mouse tissue experiments, the scientists found that the H5N1 virus was able to infect 15 different tissues, with the highest levels seen in respiratory tissues.

Lethal pattern in ferrets
Meanwhile, the team infected ferrets with a high dose of the virus from the dairy worker, and the infection pattern was more similar to human infections than mice infections. Ferrets are known as one of the best animal models for influenza in humans, because clinical signs of disease and transmission are similar.

All ferrets died within 5 days, and tissue sampling found the virus in all types, with the highest levels in the animals' respiratory tissues. In contrast, earlier research using a bovine H5N1 virus to infect ferrets found that the infections were severe, but not as lethal.

To gauge respiratory transmission, the team placed healthy ferrets in cages next to ferrets that were infected with different doses of the virus from the dairy worker. From 17% to 33% of ferrets in adjacent cages were infected by respiratory droplets, suggesting that the virus from humans can spread among mammals by that route, but with limited efficiency. All directly infected ferrets died within 6 days.

"Based in these observations, every effort should be made to contain HPAI [highly pathogenic avian influenza] H5N1 outbreaks in dairy cattle to limit the possibility of further human infections," they wrote.

California reports another suspected case

California today reported another suspected human H5N1 infection, which if confirmed by the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) would raise the state's total 16.

The CDC on October 25 confirmed 3 more infections in Washington poultry cullers, bringing the national total to 34. Once the California infection is confirmed by the CDC, the national total would rise to 35.

Virus strikes more cows, poultry
Meanwhile, the surge in outbreaks continues in California dairy cattle. The US Department of Agriculture (USDA) Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service (APHIS) has confirmed 41 more outbreaks, raising the state's total to 178 and the national total to 380 from 14 states.

Also, APHIS confirmed more outbreaks in poultry in the West, this time in Oregon, including an egg-laying farm in Clackamas County that has 146,000 birds and a backyard facility in Crook County.

The agency also confirmed an outbreak at another broiler farm in Tulare County, California, and another in backyard poultry in Washington.

October 28, 2024
In experiments designed to learn more about the threat from the H5N1 avian flu virus spreading from cows to people, researchers found that an isolate from a sick dairy worker may be capable of replicating in human airway cells, is pathogenic in mice and ferrets, and can transmit among ferrets by respiratory droplets.

The team, based at the University of Wisconsin at Madison and Japan, reported its findings today in Nature. Working in a high-containment lab, the researchers used an H5N1 isolate grown from the eye of a dairy worker who had experienced conjunctivitis after exposure to infected cows.

They found that the virus has a PB2-E627K mutation that has been seen in H5N1 viruses that replicate in mammals.

In their multipart investigation, they found that the virus was sensitive to most antivirals, including favipiravir, baloxavir marboxil, and zanamivir, but was less sensitive to oseltamivir, according to a press release from the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID), which funded much of the work.

Tests using human cornea and lung cells found that the virus was able to replicate. And, in mouse tissue experiments, the scientists found that the H5N1 virus was able to infect 15 different tissues, with the highest levels seen in respiratory tissues.

Lethal pattern in ferrets
Meanwhile, the team infected ferrets with a high dose of the virus from the dairy worker, and the infection pattern was more similar to human infections than mice infections. Ferrets are known as one of the best animal models for influenza in humans, because clinical signs of disease and transmission are similar.

All ferrets died within 5 days, and tissue sampling found the virus in all types, with the highest levels in the animals' respiratory tissues. In contrast, earlier research using a bovine H5N1 virus to infect ferrets found that the infections were severe, but not as lethal.

To gauge respiratory transmission, the team placed healthy ferrets in cages next to ferrets that were infected with different doses of the virus from the dairy worker. From 17% to 33% of ferrets in adjacent cages were infected by respiratory droplets, suggesting that the virus from humans can spread among mammals by that route, but with limited efficiency. All directly infected ferrets died within 6 days.

"Based in these observations, every effort should be made to contain HPAI [highly pathogenic avian influenza] H5N1 outbreaks in dairy cattle to limit the possibility of further human infections," they wrote.

California reports another suspected case

California today reported another suspected human H5N1 infection, which if confirmed by the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) would raise the state's total 16.

The CDC on October 25 confirmed 3 more infections in Washington poultry cullers, bringing the national total to 34. Once the California infection is confirmed by the CDC, the national total would rise to 35.

Virus strikes more cows, poultry
Meanwhile, the surge in outbreaks continues in California dairy cattle. The US Department of Agriculture (USDA) Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service (APHIS) has confirmed 41 more outbreaks, raising the state's total to 178 and the national total to 380 from 14 states.

Also, APHIS confirmed more outbreaks in poultry in the West, this time in Oregon, including an egg-laying farm in Clackamas County that has 146,000 birds and a backyard facility in Crook County.

The agency also confirmed an outbreak at another broiler farm in Tulare County, California, and another in backyard poultry in Washington.

I previously worked in the emergency department at a local hospital that mandated the flu vaccine (this was prior to covid so I imagine they have also put this in place for that too). They did not allow for philosophical exemption, however, a religious exemption could be obtained.
I compiled my letter of exemption request after researching and reviewing information that others had posted online who were successful with receiving an exemption in the healthcare field. Back in 2013, when I compiled this, there weren't very many of us trying to do this, and it was difficult to find anyone posting about this online (yes, I've been a "rebel" for a long time lol). Fast forward to today, and I know there are many people who may be in a similar situation now and not wanting to be forced to take a vaccine as a condition of employment. I am sharing my letter that I submitted to my employer  for anyone to read and use for information or inspiration if you are in a situation where your employer is mandating you to be vaccinated.

Please share with anyone who may find this helpful! Obviously at this point any letters of this nature would need to be revised to include information regarding covid vaccines as well. Otherwise, I hope this can help someone out there who feels like they don't have a choice. You do!

In experiments designed to learn more about the threat from the H5N1 avian flu virus spreading from cows to people, researchers found that an isolate from a sick dairy worker may be capable of replicating in human airway cells, is pathogenic in mice and ferrets, and can transmit among ferrets by respiratory droplets.

The team, based at the University of Wisconsin at Madison and Japan, reported its findings today in Nature. Working in a high-containment lab, the researchers used an H5N1 isolate grown from the eye of a dairy worker who had experienced conjunctivitis after exposure to infected cows.

They found that the virus has a PB2-E627K mutation that has been seen in H5N1 viruses that replicate in mammals.

In their multipart investigation, they found that the virus was sensitive to most antivirals, including favipiravir, baloxavir marboxil, and zanamivir, but was less sensitive to oseltamivir, according to a press release from the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID), which funded much of the work.

Tests using human cornea and lung cells found that the virus was able to replicate. And, in mouse tissue experiments, the scientists found that the H5N1 virus was able to infect 15 different tissues, with the highest levels seen in respiratory tissues.

Lethal pattern in ferrets
Meanwhile, the team infected ferrets with a high dose of the virus from the dairy worker, and the infection pattern was more similar to human infections than mice infections. Ferrets are known as one of the best animal models for influenza in humans, because clinical signs of disease and transmission are similar.

All ferrets died within 5 days, and tissue sampling found the virus in all types, with the highest levels in the animals' respiratory tissues. In contrast, earlier research using a bovine H5N1 virus to infect ferrets found that the infections were severe, but not as lethal.

To gauge respiratory transmission, the team placed healthy ferrets in cages next to ferrets that were infected with different doses of the virus from the dairy worker. From 17% to 33% of ferrets in adjacent cages were infected by respiratory droplets, suggesting that the virus from humans can spread among mammals by that route, but with limited efficiency. All directly infected ferrets died within 6 days.

"Based in these observations, every effort should be made to contain HPAI [highly pathogenic avian influenza] H5N1 outbreaks in dairy cattle to limit the possibility of further human infections," they wrote.

California reports another suspected case

California today reported another suspected human H5N1 infection, which if confirmed by the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) would raise the state's total 16.

The CDC on October 25 confirmed 3 more infections in Washington poultry cullers, bringing the national total to 34. Once the California infection is confirmed by the CDC, the national total would rise to 35.

Virus strikes more cows, poultry
Meanwhile, the surge in outbreaks continues in California dairy cattle. The US Department of Agriculture (USDA) Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service (APHIS) has confirmed 41 more outbreaks, raising the state's total to 178 and the national total to 380 from 14 states.

Also, APHIS confirmed more outbreaks in poultry in the West, this time in Oregon, including an egg-laying farm in Clackamas County that has 146,000 birds and a backyard facility in Crook County.

The agency also confirmed an outbreak at another broiler farm in Tulare County, California, and another in backyard poultry in Washington.

If you have a mystery medical illness, share every single possible symptom you have, even if it seems unrelated 

One time I went to the doctor and they said it was just the flu and to just go back home. 

Then, just in passing, I mentioned that it hurt to pee. They immediately knew from that piece of evidence that it was much more serious and I should go to the hospital immediately. 

I ended up having to stay in the hospital for a week and if I had waited a few more days, I would have had to have surgery. 

The lesson I learned from this is to share all of your symptoms, even if they seem really unrelated. 

They might actually be related and the clue necessary to solve it.

A week after Washington reported human cases of bird flu in the state, officials have announced that three of those cases had traveled to Oregon during their infection and were monitored during their stay.

All three cases of highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) were reported in Washington after they were exposed to poultry that tested positive for the virus on Oct. 15. As of Thursday, Oct. 31, there have been nine total cases in Washington â€” including those who had traveled to Oregon.

Oregon Health Authority officials say the cases have returned to Washington and will continue to be monitored by Washington health staff until 10 days following their last exposure.

â€œAt this time, the risk for the general public remains low,â€ Dr. Melissa Sutton with Oregon Public Health said in a statement. â€œPeople who have had close or prolonged, unprotected exposures to infected birds or other animals, or to environments contaminated by infected birds or other animals, are at increased risk of infection.â€

Washington Department of Health announced another bird flu case that led to 800,000 euthanized birds in Franklin County after they all tested positive on Oct. 15. Another case was recorded at a Clackamas County commercial poultry farm, and those birds were also euthanized to limit the spread of the disease.

It is not clear which Clackamas County poultry facility was impacted in this case, but the ODA said the operation consisted of 150,000 birds.

So far, there have been no human cases of HPAI that originated in Oregon.

The ER is only for life or limb threatening issues like sudden chest pain, difficulty breathing, loss of consciousness, trauma, compound fractures, severe abdominal pain, or the worst headache of your life, etc. 

Urgent Care is for colds/flu (although staying home is even better), rashes with a fever (over 101), breaks/sprains, uncontrolled vomiting/diarrhea, UTIs, stitches, vaginal bleeding, minor car accidents, etc. Things you canâ€™t wait a week to be addressed but wonâ€™t kill you right now. 

Your PCP is for back pain, chronic issues, pregnancy tests, prescription refills, ingrown toenails, abscesses, rashes, STDs, vaginal discharge, chronic cough, disability, diagnosing symptoms, etc. 

The ER is not for work notes, pregnancy tests, tooth pain, hangovers, fevers under 103, or medication refills. 

Calling an ambulance will not get you seen any faster in the ER  nor will complaining about the wait. If youâ€™re well enough to complain, you probably shouldnâ€™t be in an ER. 

Donâ€™t be THAT patient that makes us roll our eyes and clogs up the ER. 

Hopefully this helps direct you to the right place to get your care.

What are the symptoms of fever 
*General Symptoms (30)*

1. Elevated body temperature (above 100.4Â°F)
2. Chills
3. Sweating
4. Headache
5. Fatigue
6. Weakness
7. Muscle aches
8. Joint pain

12. Abdominal pain
13. Loss of appetite
14. Thirst
15. Dry mouth
16. Sore throat
17. Cough
18. Runny nose
19. Stuffy nose
20. Sinus pressure
21-30. Various combinations of above symptoms

*Respiratory Symptoms (20)*

1. Coughing
2. Wheezing
3. Shortness of breath
4. Chest tightness
5. Chest pain
6. Difficulty breathing
7. Rapid breathing
8. Shallow breathing

1. Nausea

3. Sore joints
4. Muscle weakness
5. General feeling of illness

- Not everyone experiences all symptoms.
- Severity and combinations of symptoms vary.
- Fever can be a symptom of various underlying conditions.
- Consult a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Definition :
 Bacterial fever is an infection caused by bacteria that leads to a high body temperature (fever) and other symptoms.
Symptoms :
-High body temperature (fever)
-Chills
-Sweat
-Headache
-Muscle aches
-Cough or sore throat
-Urinary tract infection (UTI) symptoms (e.g., burning during urination)
-Skin infections (e.g., redness, swelling, warmth)
Treatment :
-Antibiotics (prescribed by a doctor)
-Rest and hydration (plenty of fluids)
-Over-the-counter medications (e.g., Panadol ) for fever reduction
-Pain relief medications (e.g., acetaminophen, ibuprofen)
-Warm compresses for skin infections
-Urinary tract infection (UTI) treatment (e.g., antibiotics)
Note: 
Always consult a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment. Antibiotics only work against bacterial infections, not viral infections!

October 28, 2024
In experiments designed to learn more about the threat from the H5N1 avian flu virus spreading from cows to people, researchers found that an isolate from a sick dairy worker may be capable of replicating in human airway cells, is pathogenic in mice and ferrets, and can transmit among ferrets by respiratory droplets.

The team, based at the University of Wisconsin at Madison and Japan, reported its findings today in Nature. Working in a high-containment lab, the researchers used an H5N1 isolate grown from the eye of a dairy worker who had experienced conjunctivitis after exposure to infected cows.

They found that the virus has a PB2-E627K mutation that has been seen in H5N1 viruses that replicate in mammals.

In their multipart investigation, they found that the virus was sensitive to most antivirals, including favipiravir, baloxavir marboxil, and zanamivir, but was less sensitive to oseltamivir, according to a press release from the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID), which funded much of the work.

Tests using human cornea and lung cells found that the virus was able to replicate. And, in mouse tissue experiments, the scientists found that the H5N1 virus was able to infect 15 different tissues, with the highest levels seen in respiratory tissues.

Lethal pattern in ferrets
Meanwhile, the team infected ferrets with a high dose of the virus from the dairy worker, and the infection pattern was more similar to human infections than mice infections. Ferrets are known as one of the best animal models for influenza in humans, because clinical signs of disease and transmission are similar.

All ferrets died within 5 days, and tissue sampling found the virus in all types, with the highest levels in the animals' respiratory tissues. In contrast, earlier research using a bovine H5N1 virus to infect ferrets found that the infections were severe, but not as lethal.

To gauge respiratory transmission, the team placed healthy ferrets in cages next to ferrets that were infected with different doses of the virus from the dairy worker. From 17% to 33% of ferrets in adjacent cages were infected by respiratory droplets, suggesting that the virus from humans can spread among mammals by that route, but with limited efficiency. All directly infected ferrets died within 6 days.

"Based in these observations, every effort should be made to contain HPAI [highly pathogenic avian influenza] H5N1 outbreaks in dairy cattle to limit the possibility of further human infections," they wrote.

California reports another suspected case

California today reported another suspected human H5N1 infection, which if confirmed by the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) would raise the state's total 16.

The CDC on October 25 confirmed 3 more infections in Washington poultry cullers, bringing the national total to 34. Once the California infection is confirmed by the CDC, the national total would rise to 35.

Virus strikes more cows, poultry
Meanwhile, the surge in outbreaks continues in California dairy cattle. The US Department of Agriculture (USDA) Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service (APHIS) has confirmed 41 more outbreaks, raising the state's total to 178 and the national total to 380 from 14 states.

Also, APHIS confirmed more outbreaks in poultry in the West, this time in Oregon, including an egg-laying farm in Clackamas County that has 146,000 birds and a backyard facility in Crook County.

The agency also confirmed an outbreak at another broiler farm in Tulare County, California, and another in backyard poultry in Washington.

October 28, 2024
In experiments designed to learn more about the threat from the H5N1 avian flu virus spreading from cows to people, researchers found that an isolate from a sick dairy worker may be capable of replicating in human airway cells, is pathogenic in mice and ferrets, and can transmit among ferrets by respiratory droplets.

The team, based at the University of Wisconsin at Madison and Japan, reported its findings today in Nature. Working in a high-containment lab, the researchers used an H5N1 isolate grown from the eye of a dairy worker who had experienced conjunctivitis after exposure to infected cows.

They found that the virus has a PB2-E627K mutation that has been seen in H5N1 viruses that replicate in mammals.

In their multipart investigation, they found that the virus was sensitive to most antivirals, including favipiravir, baloxavir marboxil, and zanamivir, but was less sensitive to oseltamivir, according to a press release from the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID), which funded much of the work.

Tests using human cornea and lung cells found that the virus was able to replicate. And, in mouse tissue experiments, the scientists found that the H5N1 virus was able to infect 15 different tissues, with the highest levels seen in respiratory tissues.

Lethal pattern in ferrets
Meanwhile, the team infected ferrets with a high dose of the virus from the dairy worker, and the infection pattern was more similar to human infections than mice infections. Ferrets are known as one of the best animal models for influenza in humans, because clinical signs of disease and transmission are similar.

All ferrets died within 5 days, and tissue sampling found the virus in all types, with the highest levels in the animals' respiratory tissues. In contrast, earlier research using a bovine H5N1 virus to infect ferrets found that the infections were severe, but not as lethal.

To gauge respiratory transmission, the team placed healthy ferrets in cages next to ferrets that were infected with different doses of the virus from the dairy worker. From 17% to 33% of ferrets in adjacent cages were infected by respiratory droplets, suggesting that the virus from humans can spread among mammals by that route, but with limited efficiency. All directly infected ferrets died within 6 days.

"Based in these observations, every effort should be made to contain HPAI [highly pathogenic avian influenza] H5N1 outbreaks in dairy cattle to limit the possibility of further human infections," they wrote.

California reports another suspected case

California today reported another suspected human H5N1 infection, which if confirmed by the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) would raise the state's total 16.

The CDC on October 25 confirmed 3 more infections in Washington poultry cullers, bringing the national total to 34. Once the California infection is confirmed by the CDC, the national total would rise to 35.

Virus strikes more cows, poultry
Meanwhile, the surge in outbreaks continues in California dairy cattle. The US Department of Agriculture (USDA) Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service (APHIS) has confirmed 41 more outbreaks, raising the state's total to 178 and the national total to 380 from 14 states.

Also, APHIS confirmed more outbreaks in poultry in the West, this time in Oregon, including an egg-laying farm in Clackamas County that has 146,000 birds and a backyard facility in Crook County.

The agency also confirmed an outbreak at another broiler farm in Tulare County, California, and another in backyard poultry in Washington.

I compiled my letter of exemption request after researching and reviewing information that others had posted online who were successful with receiving an exemption in the healthcare field. Back in 2013, when I compiled this, there weren't very many of us trying to do this, and it was difficult to find anyone posting about this online (yes, I've been a "rebel" for a long time lol). Fast forward to today, and I know there are many people who may be in a similar situation now and not wanting to be forced to take a vaccine as a condition of employment. I am sharing my letter that I submitted to my employer  for anyone to read and use for information or inspiration if you are in a situation where your employer is mandating you to be vaccinated.

Please share with anyone who may find this helpful! Obviously at this point any letters of this nature would need to be revised to include information regarding covid vaccines as well. Otherwise, I hope this can help someone out there who feels like they don't have a choice. You do!

Of course, when the shots failed, the calculus changed. Why suffer through a post-vaccine illness only to then become sick with the virus anyway?  It's common sense not to do this.

https://t.co/owowQHJPEq

October 28, 2024
In experiments designed to learn more about the threat from the H5N1 avian flu virus spreading from cows to people, researchers found that an isolate from a sick dairy worker may be capable of replicating in human airway cells, is pathogenic in mice and ferrets, and can transmit among ferrets by respiratory droplets.

The team, based at the University of Wisconsin at Madison and Japan, reported its findings today in Nature. Working in a high-containment lab, the researchers used an H5N1 isolate grown from the eye of a dairy worker who had experienced conjunctivitis after exposure to infected cows.

They found that the virus has a PB2-E627K mutation that has been seen in H5N1 viruses that replicate in mammals.

In their multipart investigation, they found that the virus was sensitive to most antivirals, including favipiravir, baloxavir marboxil, and zanamivir, but was less sensitive to oseltamivir, according to a press release from the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID), which funded much of the work.

Tests using human cornea and lung cells found that the virus was able to replicate. And, in mouse tissue experiments, the scientists found that the H5N1 virus was able to infect 15 different tissues, with the highest levels seen in respiratory tissues.

Lethal pattern in ferrets
Meanwhile, the team infected ferrets with a high dose of the virus from the dairy worker, and the infection pattern was more similar to human infections than mice infections. Ferrets are known as one of the best animal models for influenza in humans, because clinical signs of disease and transmission are similar.

All ferrets died within 5 days, and tissue sampling found the virus in all types, with the highest levels in the animals' respiratory tissues. In contrast, earlier research using a bovine H5N1 virus to infect ferrets found that the infections were severe, but not as lethal.

To gauge respiratory transmission, the team placed healthy ferrets in cages next to ferrets that were infected with different doses of the virus from the dairy worker. From 17% to 33% of ferrets in adjacent cages were infected by respiratory droplets, suggesting that the virus from humans can spread among mammals by that route, but with limited efficiency. All directly infected ferrets died within 6 days.

"Based in these observations, every effort should be made to contain HPAI [highly pathogenic avian influenza] H5N1 outbreaks in dairy cattle to limit the possibility of further human infections," they wrote.

California reports another suspected case

California today reported another suspected human H5N1 infection, which if confirmed by the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) would raise the state's total 16.

The CDC on October 25 confirmed 3 more infections in Washington poultry cullers, bringing the national total to 34. Once the California infection is confirmed by the CDC, the national total would rise to 35.

Virus strikes more cows, poultry
Meanwhile, the surge in outbreaks continues in California dairy cattle. The US Department of Agriculture (USDA) Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service (APHIS) has confirmed 41 more outbreaks, raising the state's total to 178 and the national total to 380 from 14 states.

Also, APHIS confirmed more outbreaks in poultry in the West, this time in Oregon, including an egg-laying farm in Clackamas County that has 146,000 birds and a backyard facility in Crook County.

The agency also confirmed an outbreak at another broiler farm in Tulare County, California, and another in backyard poultry in Washington.

If you have a mystery medical illness, share every single possible symptom you have, even if it seems unrelated 

One time I went to the doctor and they said it was just the flu and to just go back home. 

Then, just in passing, I mentioned that it hurt to pee. They immediately knew from that piece of evidence that it was much more serious and I should go to the hospital immediately. 

I ended up having to stay in the hospital for a week and if I had waited a few more days, I would have had to have surgery. 

The lesson I learned from this is to share all of your symptoms, even if they seem really unrelated. 

They might actually be related and the clue necessary to solve it.

A week after Washington reported human cases of bird flu in the state, officials have announced that three of those cases had traveled to Oregon during their infection and were monitored during their stay.

All three cases of highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) were reported in Washington after they were exposed to poultry that tested positive for the virus on Oct. 15. As of Thursday, Oct. 31, there have been nine total cases in Washington â€” including those who had traveled to Oregon.

Oregon Health Authority officials say the cases have returned to Washington and will continue to be monitored by Washington health staff until 10 days following their last exposure.

â€œAt this time, the risk for the general public remains low,â€ Dr. Melissa Sutton with Oregon Public Health said in a statement. â€œPeople who have had close or prolonged, unprotected exposures to infected birds or other animals, or to environments contaminated by infected birds or other animals, are at increased risk of infection.â€

Washington Department of Health announced another bird flu case that led to 800,000 euthanized birds in Franklin County after they all tested positive on Oct. 15. Another case was recorded at a Clackamas County commercial poultry farm, and those birds were also euthanized to limit the spread of the disease.

It is not clear which Clackamas County poultry facility was impacted in this case, but the ODA said the operation consisted of 150,000 birds.

So far, there have been no human cases of HPAI that originated in Oregon.

The ER is only for life or limb threatening issues like sudden chest pain, difficulty breathing, loss of consciousness, trauma, compound fractures, severe abdominal pain, or the worst headache of your life, etc. 

Urgent Care is for colds/flu (although staying home is even better), rashes with a fever (over 101), breaks/sprains, uncontrolled vomiting/diarrhea, UTIs, stitches, vaginal bleeding, minor car accidents, etc. Things you canâ€™t wait a week to be addressed but wonâ€™t kill you right now. 

Your PCP is for back pain, chronic issues, pregnancy tests, prescription refills, ingrown toenails, abscesses, rashes, STDs, vaginal discharge, chronic cough, disability, diagnosing symptoms, etc. 

The ER is not for work notes, pregnancy tests, tooth pain, hangovers, fevers under 103, or medication refills. 

Calling an ambulance will not get you seen any faster in the ER  nor will complaining about the wait. If youâ€™re well enough to complain, you probably shouldnâ€™t be in an ER. 

Donâ€™t be THAT patient that makes us roll our eyes and clogs up the ER. 

Hopefully this helps direct you to the right place to get your care.

A week after Washington reported human cases of bird flu in the state, officials have announced that three of those cases had traveled to Oregon during their infection and were monitored during their stay.

Oregon Health Authority officials say the cases have returned to Washington and will continue to be monitored by Washington health staff until 10 days following their last exposure.

â€œAt this time, the risk for the general public remains low,â€ Dr. Melissa Sutton with Oregon Public Health said in a statement. â€œPeople who have had close or prolonged, unprotected exposures to infected birds or other animals, or to environments contaminated by infected birds or other animals, are at increased risk of infection.â€

Washington Department of Health announced another bird flu case that led to 800,000 euthanized birds in Franklin County after they all tested positive on Oct. 15. Another case was recorded at a Clackamas County commercial poultry farm, and those birds were also euthanized to limit the spread of the disease.

It is not clear which Clackamas County poultry facility was impacted in this case, but the ODA said the operation consisted of 150,000 birds.

A week after Washington reported human cases of bird flu in the state, officials have announced that three of those cases had traveled to Oregon during their infection and were monitored during their stay.

All three cases of highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) were reported in Washington after they were exposed to poultry that tested positive for the virus on Oct. 15. As of Thursday, Oct. 31, there have been nine total cases in Washington â€” including those who had traveled to Oregon.

Oregon Health Authority officials say the cases have returned to Washington and will continue to be monitored by Washington health staff until 10 days following their last exposure.

â€œAt this time, the risk for the general public remains low,â€ Dr. Melissa Sutton with Oregon Public Health said in a statement. â€œPeople who have had close or prolonged, unprotected exposures to infected birds or other animals, or to environments contaminated by infected birds or other animals, are at increased risk of infection.â€

Washington Department of Health announced another bird flu case that led to 800,000 euthanized birds in Franklin County after they all tested positive on Oct. 15. Another case was recorded at a Clackamas County commercial poultry farm, and those birds were also euthanized to limit the spread of the disease.

It is not clear which Clackamas County poultry facility was impacted in this case, but the ODA said the operation consisted of 150,000 birds.

The European Union is facing a rapid spread of bird flu, with 62 outbreaks reported on poultry farms since August 1. Most cases are concentrated in eastern EU regions, raising fears of a crisis similar to past seasons that resulted in the loss of tens of millions of birds.

Poland, the EU's largest poultry producer, has already culled 1.8 million birds, including 1.4 million from a single farm in Sroda Wielkopolska. In response to rising cases, France has strengthened its biosecurity measures to prevent further spread.
